sentences: John Elefante (born March 18, 1958) is an American singer-songwriter, instrumentalist, and Record producer.
He is known for his tenure as frontman of the rock group Kansas and is currently touring with several groups that have featured members from classic rock bands.
Early years ==

As an artist, his credits include writing and singing lead vocals on three multi-platinum albums; as producer, his albums have earned numerous GMA Dove Awards, four Grammy Awards (most recently in 2000) and ten Grammy nominations.

As an artist, his credits include writing and singing lead vocals on three multi-platinum albums; as producer, his albums have earned numerous GMA Dove Awards, four Grammy Awards (most recently in 2000) and ten Grammy nominations.
He has maintained a close working relationship with his brother, Dino (co-writer of several Kansas songs), throughout his career and has been married since 1986 and has three children.
Elefante's career began in earnest when he auditioned as the new lead singer and keyboardist for Kansas, in late 1981.
The previous year, the band was one of the top-grossing concert acts in the world.
Although several of the top vocalists of the day applied for the job (e.g. Sammy Hagar, Doug Pinnick, Jim Stafford), Elefante received the part.
On 1982's Vinyl Confessions, he sang the No. 4 Billboard Mainstream Rock hit, "Play the Game Tonight".
On 1982's Vinyl Confessions, he sang the No. 4 Billboard Mainstream Rock hit, "Play the Game Tonight".
The next year, on the following album, Drastic Measures, he wrote "Fight Fire with Fire", which remains the band's highest charting single at No. 3 (Mainstream Rock).
In 1984, on the retrospective collection The Best of Kansas, Elefante wrote the album's one new track, "Perfect Lover".
That same year, he left Kansas, along with Kerry Livgren and Dave Hope.
In 1985, "Young and Innocent" appeared on the soundtrack to St. Elmo's Fire and was credited to "Elefante" – a collaborative effort by John and his brother Dino Elefante.
In 1984, he produced Perfect Timing for ground-breaking Southern California group, Sweet Comfort Band.

In 1987 while producing a various artists album called California Metal, the album's production team of John and Dino Elefante ended up one track short and they decided to add a song written for Kansas called "Wasn't It Love" (originally entitled "What About Love") under the name Mastedon.
Closing out the decade, Elefante had produced five major label albums, and performed on 12.
Over the next five years, Elefante worked at an almost frenetic pace as one of the most in-demand producers in Nashville.
Elefante began focusing on heavier music in the early 1990s.
Mastedon's first release was titled It's a Jungle Out There! (1989).
A year later, the band released Lofcaudio.
Unfortunately, John and Dino's production schedule preempted any touring to commercially support the album (though the band did appear at least one Christian rock festival, Cornerstone, in 1991).
To this day, they are considered classics in the genre.
Most of the music they produced on in the next 10 years was released on it.
They broke ground on the 28,000-square-foot (2,600 m2) Sound Kitchen in 1993.

Elefante started a new major-distributed label with his brother in 2003, Selectric Records.
Along with co-managing the label with his brother, he produced 10 albums over the next three years.
In late 2006, Elefante took this opportunity to consider something he had never done in his career: catch his breath.
This proved more challenging than expected, and despite his best intentions, he served as producer on three albums in 2007.
Elefante finished the decade with a new Mastedon album, 3, featuring former Kansas bandmate Kerry Livgren.
== 2010 and onward ==
